1 Life Sciences 1 a 
An Integrated Introduction to the Life Sciences: 
Chemistry, Molecular Biology, and Cell Biology  
Fall 2014  
Robert Lue    Daniel Kahne  
Richard Losick    Susan Mango  
 
What are the fundamental features of living systems? What are the molecules that 
impart these features, and how do their chemical properties explain their biological 
roles? The answers to these questions form the basis for an understanding of the 
molecules  of life, the cell, disease, and drug design . Whereas the relevant  scientific 
disciplines addressing these topics are traditionally presented  in separate courses, we 
examine the above concepts through an integrated presentation of chemistry, 
molecular biol ogy, biochemistry, and cell biology . These subjects are explored using 
three specific examples : the cell as the fundamental unit of life, the biology and 
treatment of HIV, and the biology and treatment of cancer.  
 
The course consists of two 90 minute lectu res, along with a three -hour discussion /lab 
section each week.  
 
LECTURE LOCATION and TIME : Science Center Hall B, Tu Th 1 -2:30pm  
 
COURSE WEBSITE : ls1a.org  (https://harvard.instructure.com/courses/775 )  
 
COURSE EMAIL : lsci1a@fas.harvard.edu  (please email us with questions and concerns!)  
 
PRECEPTORS : Dr. Martin Samuels  and Dr. Aaron Garner  
 
Head TF: Dr. Kate Mirkin  
 
Lectures  
Lectures are held on Tuesdays and Thursdays  from 1 - 2:30 PM in Science Center Hall B. 
Attending lecture is a crucial component of learning the material presented in this 
course, and it cannot be adequately replaced by other means. Please a rrive no later 
than 1:07 PM, as lectures and Break -Outs ( see below) will begin promptly.  
 2  
Required Readings  
Lecture slides will be provided online (on the “ Pre-Lecture Slides ” page of the course 
website) before  each lecture so you can either print them out to take notes manually or 
you can take notes on them using your laptop and annotating software. Each lecture will 
also have a Lecture Pre -Gam e, which is a short reading including a few questions, that 
you are expected to complete before lecture (see Lecture Pre -Games  below). Complete 
lecture notes will be supplied online (on the “ Post -Lecture Notes ” page of the course 
website ) after  each lecture . These post -lecture notes  serve as the required readings for 
this course. There are no required textbooks.    
 
If you would like additional reading s to clarify certain  concept s, we suggest the following 
two textbooks  of which t here are several copies on reserve in Cabot Library.  
 
1. McMurry & Castellion:  General,  Organic, and Biological Chemistry  (published by 
Prentice Hall).  
2. Alberts et al .: Essential Cell Biology  (published by Garland Science)  
 
A free online  version of Alberts (along with several other textbooks) can also be found 
online using the National Center for Biotechnology Information  (“NCBI”) server , which 
can be found at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21054/ . Just enter a topic you 
are interested in into the search field. All of their textbooks can be searched using 
http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/ . 
 
Lecture Break -Outs  
A Break -Out is a n interactive, all hands activity or  discussion during lecture that 
culminates in a multiple choice question based on concepts taught in lecture. Answ ers 
to Break -Out questions will be submitted  using a either a cell phone or a laptop via a 
program called PollEverywhere  (for instructions on how to sign up for  a PollEverywhere  
account,  please see the Syllabus and Course Information Page ). Please email us  if you 
have access to neither  a laptop nor a cell phone . 
 
Brea k-Outs will occur during the lecture throughout  the entire  semester. Participating in 
20 break -outs adds up to 5% of the final course grade . 
 
Note:  To account for the fact that there will be no Break -Out make  ups even in the 
event of excused absences, there will be more than 20 Break -Outs throughout the 
semester but only 20 scores will contr ibute towards the final grade. Students must 
submit their own  answer s (please see the “ Academic Integrity Policy ” information  sheet  
on the Syllabus and Course Information Page ), so please do not be tempted to submit 
break -out responses for someone else . 
 
 
 
 3 Lecture Pre -Games  
There is a Lecture Pre-Game  due prior to each lecture, unless otherwise noted. Pre-
games are short, straightforward assignments that either introduce a new skill or 
concept that the lecture wil l build upon or will reinforce concepts taught in the prior 
lecture. The L ecture Pre-Games make use of a website called Sapling Technology  and 
typically consist of a short read ing and a short series of questions that allow the 
lecturers to see which skills and concepts the class has mastered and which should be 
emphasized in lecture. (For instructions on how to sign up for a Sapling Technology 
account, please see the Syllabus and Course Information Page .) These Lecture Pre-
Games are due prior to the start o f each lecture, and completing them with your best  
effort  constitute s 5% of the final course  grade.  The Lecture -Pre Games, similar to the 
Lecture Break -Outs, are graded according to completion  and effort  instead of being 
graded according to the accuracy of the answers submitted.  
 
Sections  
Sections are three hours long and take pla ce each week outside of lecture. Section 
complement s the course by reinforc ing material  presented in the lectures and readings , 
but in a small group setting . They are led by teaching fellows and  combine both 
discussion  and laboratory  components. You will get the  most benefi t out of section if  
you come prepare d for discussion and laboratory . Sections , together with office hours,  
are an excellent opportunity for you to ask your teaching fellow  any questions you may 
have about the course material.  
 
Attendance at all sections is  required , and participation, together with graded 
assignments and problem sets, account s for a substantial portion of a student’s  grade. 
No student may obtain a passing grade in the course without attending each  section.  If 
you are ill or need to switch sections, please email the course preceptors . The handouts 
provided in section, including the answers, will be posted on the course website at the 
end of each week.  
 
To enter you r section time preferences, please visit http://www.section.fas.harvard.edu  
before 11:59 PM on Friday , September 5th. Section assignments will be sent out by 
email by 11:59 PM on Monday , September 8th and section s will begin on Wednesday, 
Sep. 10th. Requests to change section s must be addressed to the course preceptors at 
lsci1a@fas.harvard.edu , and will only be considered for time  conflicts with other 
acad emic courses . 
 
Problem Sets  
Problem sets will be posted on the website  on Tuesday evenings and will be due no 
later than 6 :00 PM on the following Monday  (listed in the course syllabus ). Problem sets 
can be turned in earlier than the due date, but no problem sets will be accepted for 
credit after the 6:00 PM deadline . Each student’s lowest problem set score will be 
dropped at the end of the semester. Students are encouraged to work in grou ps on their 
problem sets; h owever , each person must write and submit answers in his/her  own 
 4 words to receive credit  (see the “Academic Integrity Policy” information sheet) . Answer 
keys for the problem sets will be posted to the course website after the problem sets 
have been collected.  
 
In Class Evaluations (or “ICE”s)   
In Class Evaluations, or “ICE”s, are designed to eliminate infrequent, high -stakes and high -
stress midterms with more frequent, shorter assessments. Whereas we hope and expect 
that you will work on your homework and lab assignments collaboratively with your 
classmates, the ICEs are you r chance to demonstrate your individual facility  with applying 
the concepts and skills taught in the course. T he particular concepts and skills that are 
assessed in each ICE are outlined in each lecture ’s Learning Goals and Objectives.  The six 
ICEs ar e listed in the course syllabus  and the material each one covers is listed below . 
 
Three “P ractice ICE s” will be posted a week in advance  to help you prepare . In addition, 
Marty and Aaron will host a review session each Saturday afternoon prior to each ICE and 
our course facilitators will lead Student Study Networks each Sunday evening (see below).  
 
The ICEs alternate weekly with the problem sets. We hope that the In  Class Evaluations 
will hedge against cramming and rote memorization and instead incentivize the gradual 
accrual of knowledge and skills as the course progresses.  For each ICE, you will be allowed 
to bring in an index card on which you can hand written whatever you would like . (Blank 
index cards will be provided in class prior to each ICE) . 
 
No make -up In Class Evaluations will be given. If you miss an ICE, you must have a written 
medical excuse, and your ICE grade will be based on your remaining ICEs . 
 
ICE Coverage :** 
 ICE 1 cover s lectures 1 and 2  
 ICE 2 cover s lectures 5 and 6  
 ICE 3 cover s lectures 9 and 10  
 ICE 4 cover s lectures 13 and 14  
 ICE 5 cover s lectures 17 and 18  
 ICE 6 cover s lectures 21 and 22  
** Coverage includes the material presented in the Lecture Pre -Reading s and Pre -
Games for the lectures listed above.  
 
Final Evaluation  (or “ICE Cube”)  
Final exams at Harvard are typically three hour s long, but the final exam for LS 1a wi ll be 
designed to take one hour. T he three hours will still be provided if you w ould like to use 
your full time . 
 
The final consists of three “modul es,” each equivalent to an ICE . As the final evaluation 
consists of three ICE equivalents, we like to think of it as “ ICE3,” or if you pardon our bad 
 5 pun, the “ICE Cube.” The ICE Cube is therefore designed to take an hour because it 
consists of three modules ea ch of which is designed to take 20 minutes, but you are 
welcome to  spend however long you like on each module . 
 
Between the six ICEs offered during the semester and the ICE Cube , there are nine 
equivalent “ICE” modules. The lowest score from among these ni ne will be dropped 
when calculating your composite ICE/Final score . If, for example, ICE 5 is dropped, then 
your composite “ICE Tray” score would be calculated as diagrammed below.  
 
 
Alternatively, one of the ICE Cube modules can be dropped in which case  all six of the 
ICEs would be included.  
 
The Registrar’s office determines the date and time of the final exam. We will update 
the course website once we know the time and location of the ICE Cube, and y ou are 
responsible for ensuring your attendance.  
 
BLUE SKY  
The BLUE SKY  Proposal  offer s each student  the opportunity to explore an issue  that lies  
at the intersection of biology and chemistry  and propose a means to answer that 
question . The project highly encourages students to l et their imagination s run free  in 
coming up with questions : there are no barriers to the ideas that can be put forward  as 
long as the concepts underlying the proposal are underpinned by  the chemical and 
biological concepts taught in LS  1a. 
 
There will be three  required  components to BLUE SKY : proposing an idea ; then two 
weeks later drafting a one -page draft proposal ; and then a month later handing in a final 
version of your BLUE SKY Proposal . Both t he draft and the final  Proposal  should include : 
 how  the proposed topic/issue/question  relates to the interface of chem istry and 
biology  

 6  how you  propose  to answer your question  (including proposed experiments)  
 how you might interpret some of the data you anticipate  
 a concept map that connects the concepts taught in LS  1a to your proposed topic 
and the experiments intended to address the topic or other means of addressing the 
issue  
 
After sharing your idea with your peers during  section and getting feedback from your 
TF, you will then have two weeks to incorporate their fe edback in your  one-page final 
copy of your BLUE SKY  Proposal . The final one -page BLUE SKY P roposal is due on 
December 1st.  
 
The BLUE SKY  project culminates in a BLUE SKY FAIR  in Annenberg during reading period  
in which everyone is invited to share their ideas in small groups. Each small group will be 
able to nominate their favorite BLUE SKY Proposal , and the winners’ P roposals will be 
designated as “ BLUE SKY Kites ” video -taped and upload ed to the BLUE SKY Facebook 
page  for recognit ion and comment.  
 
To help guide you, t here will be section time devoted to developing the BLUE SKY  
proposals during  the semester. There is also a “BLUE SKY ” page  on the course website 
that will include instructions, BLUE SKY Toolkits describ ing various biochemical lab 
techniques, and a link to last year’s BLUE SKY Kite recordings. In addition, our 
professors, preceptors, and TFs are very  excited to discuss your ideas during office hours 
and over email.  
 
Grading  
Top eight  out o f nine ICE/Final module scores  (“ICE Tray) : 40%  
Top five out of six Problem Sets:  17.5% 
Six lab assignments  17.5% 
BLUE SKY Proposal : 10% 
Break -outs:  5% 
Lecture Pre -Games:  5% 
Section participation : 5% 
 
Letter grades are assigned at the end of the course based on the percentage of total 
points earned during the semester . That said, if you score ≥90% you are guaranteed to 
receive at least a grade of A minus, while if you score ≥80% you are guaranteed to 
receive at least a grade of B.

 7 Student Study Networks  
To further promote Life Sciences 1a as a community of learning, the course fosters  the 
formation of collaborative study networks where studen ts can discuss problem sets and 
study  for ICEs in groups. LS  1a facilitators will host these study network sessions  
throughout the semester . The student study networks are held each Sunday evening (7-
9pm) in Science Center rooms 109, 110, 111, 112, and 113 . 
 
Office Hours  
Office hours are a useful  resource that we encourage every student to attend  during the 
semester . They are a fantastic opportunity to speak individually with course staff to 
review course material, clarify confusing concepts, expand upon discussions beyond the 
scope of the lectures or discussions, or to learn more about the staff members’ interests 
and research. Please do not be anxious or afraid to approach any staff member 
(regardless of whether they have a “Prof” or a “Dr” in front of their name).  Office hour 
times for professors  and preceptors will be posted on the front page of the course  
website . Each teaching fellow will also have office hours with the times to be 
determined in each section.  All students have to opportunity to go to anyone’s office 
hours, and all of the TFs’ office hours will be posted on the “ TF Office Hours ” page of the 
course website.
